INSERT INTO `main_table` VALUES ('48', 'Verse', 'Darwish', 'Mahmoud', '', 'Maḥmūd Darwīsh', 'Munir Akash & Carolyn Forché', '', 'Munīr ʻAkash', '', 'Unfortunately it was paradise', 'selected poems', '', '', 'Palestine', 'University of California Press', 'Berkeley', '2003', 'Acknowledgments / Munir Akash -- Introduction / Munir Akash and Carolyn Forche\n\nFrom \'Fewer roses\' - 1986 (tr. Munir Akash & Carolyn Forche)\nI will slog over this road -- Another road in the road -- Were it up to me to begin again -- On this earth -- I belong there -- Addresses for the soul, outside this place -- Earth presses against us -- We journey towards a home -- We travel like all people -- Athens airport -- I talk too much -- We have the right to love Autumn -- The last train has stopped -- On the slope, higher than the sea, they slept -- He embraces his murderer -- Winds shift against us -- Neighing on the slope -- Other Barbarians will come -- They would love to see me dead -- When the martyrs go to sleep -- The night there -- We went to Aden -- Another Damascus in Damascus -- The flute cried -- In this hymn\n\nFrom \'I see what I want to see\' - 1993 (tr. Munir Akash & Carolyn Forche)\nThe Hoopoe\n\nFrom \'Why have you left the horse alone?\' - 1995 (tr. Amira el-Zein)\nI see my ghost coming from afar -- A cloud in my hands -- The kindhearted villagers -- The owl\'s night -- The everlasting Indian fig -- The lute of Ismael -- The strangers\' picnic -- The raven\'s ink -- Like the letter \"N\" in the Qur\'an -- Ivory combs -- The death of the phoenix -- Poetic regulations -- Excerpts from the Byzantine odes of Abu Firas -- The dreamers pass from one sky to another -- A rhyme for the Odes (Mu\'allaqat) -- Night that overflows my body -- The Gypsy woman has a tame sky\n\nFrom \'A bed for the stranger\' - 1999 (tr. Sinan Antoon)\nWe were without a present -- Sonnet II -- The stranger finds himself in the stranger -- The land of the stranger, the serene land -- Inanna\'s milk -- Who am I, without exile? -- Lesson from the Kama Sutra\n\nMural - 2000 (tr. Munir Akash & Carolyn Forche)\n\nThree poems - before 1986 (tr. Munir Akash & Carolyn Forche)\nA soldier dreams of white tulips -- As fate would have it -- Four personal addresses.', 'From \'Ward aqall\': Saʼaqtaʻ hādhā al-ṭarīq -- Wa-mā zāl fī al-darb darb -- Idhā kāna lī ann uʻīda al-bidāyah -- ʻAlá hādhihi al-arḍ -- Anā min hunāk -- ʻAnāwīn lil-rūḥ khārij hādhā al-makān -- Tuḍīqu binā al-arḍ -- Nasīru ilá baladin -- Nusāfir ka-al-nās -- Maṭār Athīnā -- Aqūlu kalāman kathīran -- Yuḥiqqu lanā ann nuḥibba al-kharīf -- al-Qiṭar al-akhīr tawaqqaf -- ʻAlá al-safḥ, aʻlá min al-jabal, nāmū -- Yuʻāniq qātilahu -- Tukhālifunā al-rīḥ -- Ṣahīl ʻalá al-safḥ -- Sa-yaʼtī Barābirah ākharūn -- Yuḥibbūnanī maytan -- ʻIndamā yadhhab al-shuhadāʼ ilá al-nawm -- Hunālika layl -- Dhahabnā ilá ʻAdan -- Wa-fī al-Shām Shām -- Baká al-nāy -- Afī mithli hādhā al-nashīd.\n\nFrom \'Ará mā urīd\': al-Hud´hud.\n\nFrom \'Li-mādhā tarakta al-ḥiṣān wahīdan\': Ará shabaḥī qādiman min baʻīd -- Fī yadī ghaymah -- Qarawīyūn min ghayr sūʼ -- Laylat al-būm -- Abad al-subbār -- ʻŪd Ismāʻīl -- Nuzhat al-ghurabāʼ -- Ḥibr al-ghurāb -- Ka-al-nūn fī sūrat al-Raḥmān -- Amshāṭ ʻājīyah -- Maṣraʻ al-ʻanqāʼ -- Tadābīr shiʻrīyah -- Min Rūmīyat Abī Firās al-Ḥamadānī -- Min samāʼ ilá ukhtihā yaʻbur al-ḥālimūn -- Qāfīyah min ajl al-Muʻallaqāt -- Layl yafīḍ min al-jasad -- Lil-Ghajarīyah, samāʼ mudarrabah.\n\nFrom \'Sarīr al-gharībah\': Kāna yanqaṣunā ḥāḍir -- Sūnātā II -- Wuqūʻ al-gharīb ʻalá nafsihi fī al-gharīb -- Arḍ al-gharīb, arḍ al-sakīnah -- Ḥalīb Inānā -- Man anā, dūn manfá? -- Dars min Kāmā Sūṭrā.\n\nJidārīyah -- Jundī yaḥlam bi-al-zanābiq al-bayḍāʼ -- ??? -- Arbaʻat ʻanāwīn shakhṣīyah.', '', 'Translated and edited with Sinan Antoon and Amira ek-Zein', '', 'xix ; 191 p. ; 22 cm.', '', '0520237536 (alk. paper) : 0520237544 (pbk. : alk.', '11/26/03', 'Translit-Checked', 'book');
